<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP NOTES; 
</P>
<P>
LOCAL TALENT TO PLAY BENEFIT MAY 19 FOR CHILD ABUSE VICTIMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE BOEHM, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Coach House in San Juan Capistrano will host a benefit May 19 for Stop the 
Pain Inc., a Santa Ana-based organization devoted to helping victims of child 
abuse. 
</P>
<P>
The lineup for the 6 p.m. show features an array of strong local talent. 
Performers include Kerry Getz, Ann De Jarnett and Jim Bemis, Naked Soul, Don't 
Mean Maybe, 3D Picnic, Wood &amp; Smoke and the Beat Pests. 
</P>
<P>
Advance tickets, priced at $6, are available at the Coach House and through 
Moby Disc in Westminster, Music Mart and London Exchange in Costa Mesa and Pier 
Records at UC Irvine. Tickets cost $10 at the door. Information: (714) 
496-8930. 
</P>
<P>
Other newly booked shows at the Coach House include Venice on May 25; Beat 
Farmers and Food For Feet, June 1; Shawn Colvin, June 12; Pato Banton, June 18; 
Dennis Quaid and the Swamp Tones, June 22; Albert King, June 29; and Natalie 
Cole, Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
BYRDS WON'T ROOST: The May 16 Byrds show advertised at Hamptons will not take 
place. The booking was not solidified with a deposit, according to the band's 
agent, and the group has accepted an offer to play in Tulsa, Okla., instead. 
</P>
<P>
The version of the Byrds that had been scheduled to play at Hamptons includes 
only one original Byrd, drummer Michael Clarke. A Florida judge last year 
awarded Clarke the right to continue touring under the Byrds name, throwing out 
a legal challenge that had been mounted by Clarke's better-known former band 
mates, David Crosby, Roger McGuinn and Chris Hillman. 
</P>
<P>
In January, 1989, Crosby, McGuinn and Hillman played a series of Southern 
California dates, including a show at the Coach House, as part of their failed 
attempt to wrest legal control of the Byrds name away from Clarke. 
</P>
<P>
NEW SHOWS AT IRVINE, PACIFIC: Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre puts tickets on sale 
this weekend for three shows: L.A. Guns, Y&amp;T and Circus of Power on June 
10; Erasure and Wire on June 15 and Don Henley and the Innocence Mission June 
17. 
</P>
<P>
The Erasure tickets go on sale at 9 a.m. Saturday at Music Plus Ticketmaster 
locations; priority wristbands will be issued at random starting at 8 a.m. 
Henley tickets will be available at 10 a.m. Saturday at all Ticketmaster 
locations. Tickets for the L.A. Guns show go on sale at 9 a.m. Sunday; priority 
wristbands will be handed out beginning at 8 a.m. at Music Plus Ticketmaster 
outlets only. Charge line information: (714) 740-2000 or (213) 480-3232. 
</P>
<P>
Tickets go on sale at 10 a.m. Sunday for shows at the Pacific Amphitheatre by 
the Judds; Highway 101 on Aug. 4 and K.T. Oslin, Ricky Van Shelton and Baillie 
and the Boys on Sept. 7. Charge line: (714) 634-1300. Recorded information: 
(213) 642-4242. 
</P>
</TEXT>
